defaultSECTION 5default&#xa0;defaultBranch closure and access to banking in rural communitiesdefaultBBA members recognise their responsibility in providing a network of services for their customers. Individual firms continue to view a branch 
defaultfootprint as an integral part of their service to customers and continue to compete against each other on the strength of this offering.
default 
defaultIn common with most commercial businesses, banks make
default&#xa0;
defaulttheir decisions in respect of both provision and withdrawal of b
defaultranches based upon demand and profitability. Branches will remain open if they are being used, but if the number of customers coming into the branch falls, then just like any other retail outlet, the bank will need to look carefully at whether it is still 
defaultviable to keep it open
default. 
defaultNevertheless a number of banks have committed to keep a branch open if there are no alternative banks in the vicinity. The increasing availability of cash services through ATMs, Post Offices
default (c11,000 branches in the United Kingdom)
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultand cash back via retail outlets has greatly reduced the demand for counter access in recent years.
default&#xa0;
default Direct Debits and Standing Orders have also reduced the need for over the counter bill payments.
defaultThe ways in which customers are demanding their banks pro
defaultvide services are evolving in new ways and at a tremendous speed that could not have been envisaged even 5 years ago. Offerings such as: location based services, online banking, mobile payments, faster payments and faster account switching only begin to sc
defaultratch the surface of recent developments. These services are flexible, convenient and usually provide 24 hours, 7 days a week banking service. 
defaultT
defaulthe telephone banking network has been well established for many years providing an ea
defaultsy to use service for custo
defaultmers;
default 
defaulta
defaults such many personal customers now do not need to go into a bank branch and call centres are able to deal with many other aspects of personal banking. Some banks are also trying to find more cost efficient and effective ways for small businesses to bank ca
defaultsh rather than queue up at the branch. They understand that this is a problem for small business customers and there are already systems in place for cheques. 
defaultOne recent development of interest has been from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT), whose remit i
defaults to 
defaultmake markets work well by promoting and protecting consumer interests throughout the U
defaultnited 
defaultK
defaultingdom
default. The OFT
default’s paper “Price and choice in remote communities,” published in June 2012, reports
default&#xa0;
defaulton the issues faced by remote communities
default&#xa0;
defaultwith views receive
defaultd from over 500 public bodies, companies and voluntary organisations. 
defaultThe report identifies a range of complimentary actions that businesses, including the banking sector, can take. The suggested solution for banks was to provide services to remote communi
defaultties through alternative delivery mechanisms; this included an example of mobile banking facilities where a bricks-and-mortar bank may not be available to local residents and businesses.
